1 Packages

library(mrgsolve)
library(dplyr)

2 Introduction

We are free to create data sets which (1) include observation records in addition to dosing records and (2) there is no limit to the person-to-person heterogeneity in those dosing designs.

However, it is not at all convenient to program this variability into the data set. We would rather have a programmatic way to create a list of designs and assign different designs to different individuals or groups of individuals.

2.1 Objective

  • Review tgrid objects, what they are and how are they used
  • Introduce methods for creating heterogeneity in observation schedule within a given simulation run

3 tgrid objects

  • mrgsolve tracks a simulation start and end time as well as a delta value specifying how often an observation will be made between start and end
  • There is also an additional, ad-hoc vector of simulation times (add)
  • tgrid objects abstract that functionality and allow us to create separate objects that describe a period of time using those same start/end/delta/add elements
  • Recall also that we can work with tgrid objects through operations, the most common being + … a shift in time
mod <- mread_cache("popex", modlib())

day1 <- tgrid(0,24,2)
day5 <- day1 + 5*24

des <- c(day1,day5)

des
. start:  0  end:    24  delta:  2  offset: 0  min:    0   max:    24 
. --------
. start:  0  end:    24  delta:  2  offset: 120  min:    120   max:    144 
. --------

3.1 Default behavior

Regardless how we use the tgrid object, every individual in the simulation is assigned the same grid of observation times

mod %>% 
  ev(amt=100, ii=24, addl = 9) %>%
  mrgsim(tgrid = des, nid = 10) %>% 
  plot(DV~., type = 'b')

4 Assign unique end times to each ID

  • Create an idata_set including each ID in the run
  • column includes end … this will be the simulation end time
idata <- data_frame(ID = 1:100) 
idata <- mutate(idata, end = sample(c(1,2,3,4)*168, n(), replace = TRUE))
idata

Use as_deslist to create a list of designs …

  • We look the column indicated by descol to understand how many different designs we need to make.
  • By taking descol = "end", there will be 4 different designs by virtue of the fact that we’ve got 4 different end times
des <- as_deslist(idata, descol = "end")
des
. $end_168
. start:  0  end:    168  delta:  1  offset: 0  min:    0   max:    168 
. 
. $end_336
. start:  0  end:    336  delta:  1  offset: 0  min:    0   max:    336 
. 
. $end_504
. start:  0  end:    504  delta:  1  offset: 0  min:    0   max:    504 
. 
. $end_672
. start:  0  end:    672  delta:  1  offset: 0  min:    0   max:    672 
. 
. attr(,"descol")
. [1] "end"

What whould have happened if descol = "ID"?

Now, simulate with that design list

out <- 
  mod %>% 
  idata_set(idata) %>%
  ev(amt=100, ii=24, addl = 28) %>%
  design(des) %>% 
  mrgsim(carry.out = "end")

It is required that we

  1. implement an idata_set … that is where the information is coming from and
  2. identify the idata_set prior to identifying the deslist
plot(out, DV~time|factor(end))

What if we wanted less intense samples in the 2, 3, 4 week designs but not the 1 week design?
